      <hedline>
        <hl1>Salvadorans' Secret Weapon</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ana De Jesus letter explains some of the many ways in which Salvadorans like to use Lea &amp; Perrins' Worcestershire sauce (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The officials at Lea &amp; Perrins may scratch their heads at the 450 tons of their sauce sold yearly in El Salvador, a tiny Central American country, but as a native of that country I don't find that figure surprising at all (''Toque and Dagger: the Sauce Secrets of Worcester,'' June 21).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The officials at Lea &amp; Perrins may scratch their heads at the 450 tons of their sauce sold yearly in El Salvador, a tiny Central American country, but as a native of that country I don't find that figure surprising at all (''Toque and Dagger: the Sauce Secrets of Worcester,'' June 21).</p>
        <p>Salvadorans probably use the sauce in more ways than any other people on earth. I've seen it used in salads, as a marinade and as one of the primary ingredients in our version of corn on the cob, elote loco (crazy corn). Even the slices of green mango sold on the street come in a sauce consisting of lemon, salt, hot sauce and, of course, Worcestershire.</p>
        <p>ANA DE JESUS  New York</p>
      </block>
